|\u00b5g/l|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" |* These analyses are a summation of work performed by the Toxicology Institute, Division of Laboratories and Research, New York State Department of Health and various laboratories of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and their subcontractors.\n<nowiki/>** ID \u2013 Identified but not quantified\n\nug/l \u2013 microgram per liter\n\nug/m<sup>3</sup> \u2013 microgram per cubic meter\n|}\n\n=== Consequences ===\n==== Activism ====\n[[File:Love Canal protest.jpg|thumb|right|upright|A protest by Love Canal residents, ca. 1978.]]\nIn 1976, two reporters for the ''[[Niagara Gazette|Niagara Falls Gazette]]'', David Pollak and David Russell, tested several [[sump pump]]s near Love Canal and found toxic chemicals in them. The ''Gazette'' published reports, once in October 1976 and once in November 1976, of chemical analyses of residues near the old Love Canal dumpsite indicated presence of 15 organic chemicals, including three toxic chlorinated hydrocarbons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.buffalo.edu/specialcollections/lovecanal/about/chronology.php|title=Love Canal Chronologies - Love Canal Collections - University Archives - University at Buffalo Libraries|website=library.buffalo.edu|access-date=2017-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222185203/http://library.buffalo.edu/specialcollections/lovecanal/about/chronology.php|archive-date=2017-02-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> The matter became quiet for more than a year and was then revived by reporter Michael Brown, who then investigated potential health effects by performing an informal door-to-door survey during early 1978, writing a hundred news items on toxic wastes in the area and finding birth defects and many anomalies such as enlarged feet, heads, hands, and legs. He advised the local residents to create a protest group, which was organized by resident Karen Schroeder, whose daughter had many (about a dozen) birth defects. The New York State Health Department investigated and found an abnormal incidence of miscarriages. Brown discovered the size of the canal, the presence of dioxin, the expanding contamination, and the involvement, to an extent, of the U.S. Army. Hooker threatened to sue him and he fought the firm tooth and nail for years, including on the Today Show. His book on toxic wastes, Laying Waste: The Poisoning of America By Toxic Chemicals (Pantheon), was the first written on the subject of toxic wastes and created a national firestorm, as did articles of his in The New York Times Magazine and The Atlantic Monthly. He also discovered a massive dump called the Hyde Park landfill (or Bloody Run) and the \"S-Area,\" which was leaking into the water supply for Niagara Falls. His work inspired many activists. He spoke for ten years on the college lecture circuit.\n\nBy 1978, Love Canal had become a national media event with articles referring to the neighborhood as \"a public health time bomb\", and \"one of the most appalling environmental tragedies in American history\".<ref name=\"epa1\" />  Brown, working for the local newspaper, the ''Niagara Gazette'', is credited with not only revealing the case, but establishing toxic chemical wastes as a nationwide issue as well.  Brown's book, ''Laying Waste'', examined the Love Canal disaster and many other toxic waste catastrophes nationwide.<ref>Brown, Michael, ''Laying Waste:  The Poisoning of America by Toxic Chemicals.''  New York:  Washington Square Press, 1981, ii.</ref>\n\nThe dumpsite was declared an unprecedented state emergency on August 2, 1978. Brown, who wrote more than a hundred articles concerning the dump, tested the groundwater and later found the dump was three times larger than originally thought, with possible ramifications beyond the original evacuation zone. He was also to discover that toxic [[dioxins and dioxin-like compounds|dioxins]] were there.\n\n=====Activism tactics=====\nActivism at Love Canal was initially organized by community residents Tom Heiser and [[Lois Gibbs]], with Lois Gibbs often serving as spokesperson.  Gibbs' strategies emphasized concerns for children and families of the affected area, with women taking the most prominent public and active roles{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}.  Many men also helped women in these efforts, though not always publicly{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}. Men who were hesitant to oppose Hooker Chemical openly for example, were able to contribute to the movement through increased contributions to family labor in the absence of their activist wives.<ref>''E. Blum, Love Canal Revisited: Race, Class, and Gender in Environmental Activism (2008)''</ref>\n\nIn addition to community organizing and pressuring authorities for appropriate responses, direct-action forms of activism were employed.  Tactics included protests and rallies, which were intentionally timed and planned in an effort to maximize media attention.  Such events included \"controversial\" methods such as mothers protesting while pushing strollers, marching by pregnant women, and children holding protest signs.  Notably, two EPA employees were also held hostage by activists for approximately five hours at the LCHA office, in order to bring their demands to the attention of the federal government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publicintegrity.org/environment/from-homemaker-to-hell-raiser-in-love-canal/|title=From homemaker to hell-raiser in Love Canal|website=Center for Public Integrity|access-date=2019-02-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190224231550/https://publicintegrity.org/environment/from-homemaker-to-hell-raiser-in-love-canal/|archive-date=2019-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=====Role of community organizations=====\n{{more citations needed|section|date=August 2018}}\nNumerous organizations were formed in response to the crisis at Love Canal, with members' activism emphasizing variously overlapping interests.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kansaspress.ku.edu/978-0-7006-1820-0.html|title=Love Canal Revisited|website=kansaspress.ku.edu|access-date=2018-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511081736/https://kansaspress.ku.edu/978-0-7006-1820-0.html|archive-date=2018-05-11|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to the Love Canal Homeowners Association ([[Love Canal#Lois Gibbs and the Love Canal Homeowners' Association|LCHA]]), other major organizations are the Ecumenical Taskforce (ETF), National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP), and the Concerned Love Canal Renters Association (CLCRA). These organizations are often overlooked in the story of Love Canal, according to research by Elizabeth Blum in '[https://kansaspress.ku.edu/978-0-7006-1820-0.html 'Love Canal Revisited']'.\n\nThe Ecumenical Taskforce (ETF) was a religious organization composed of volunteers from the surrounding area. In conjunction with other citizens' groups such as LCHA and LCARA, the ETF used their resources to promote environmental health and gender, class, and racial equality. {{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nThe [[NAACP]] became involved with the Love Canal issue after William Abrams Sr., president of the Niagara Falls chapter drew concerns to his wife's fatal liver failure. Abrams involvement drew attention to racial inequality present in the community and concerns about how this could affect comprehensive relocation efforts. Abrams contacted the regional NAACP director who announced that discrimination against minorities at Love Canal would be met with legal action. This involvement inspired additional support and activism, particularly on behalf of members of the renting community, many of whom were also members of the African-American and immigrant communities at the site. {{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nAnother subgroup of local residents formed the Concerned Love Canal Renters Association (CLCRA). This group's action sought to address the needs of the (largely, but not exclusively, African-American) renter community, whose interests were at times perceived to be in conflict with those of some members of the (predominantly white) property owners represented by the LCHA. {{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nIn 1980 [[Lois Gibbs]] established the Center for Health, Environment, and Justice as a continuation of her activism at Love Canal. {{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n==== Lois Gibbs and the Love Canal Homeowners' Association ====\nOn August 2, 1978, [[Lois Gibbs]], a local mother who called an election to head the Love Canal Homeowners' Association, began to rally homeowners. Her son, Michael Gibbs, began attending school in September 1977. He developed [[epilepsy]] in December, suffered from [[asthma]] and a [[urinary tract infection]], and had a low [[white blood cell]] count,<ref name=\"gibbsheroproj\">{{cite web|url=http://www.heroism.org/class/1970/gibbs.html|title=Heroism Project - 1970s - Lois Gibbs|author=|date=|website=www.heroism.org|access-date=2007-07-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006195542/http://www.heroism.org/class/1970/gibbs.html|archive-date=2007-10-06|url-status=live}}</ref>{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=26}} all associated with his exposure to the leaking chemical waste. Gibbs had learned from Brown that her neighborhood sat atop the buried chemical waste.<ref name=\"goldman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goldmanprize.org/node/103|title=Goldman Environmental Prize - Lois Gibbs|author=|date=|website=goldmanprize.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007023204/http://www.goldmanprize.org/node/103|archivedate=2007-10-07|df=}}</ref>\n\nDuring the following years, Gibbs organized an effort to investigate community concerns about the health of its residents. She and other residents made repeated complaints of strange odors and \"substances\" that surfaced in their yards. In Gibbs' neighborhood, there was a high rate of unexplained illnesses, miscarriages, and intellectual disability.{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=21}} Basements were often covered with a thick, black substance, and vegetation was dying.  In many yards, the only vegetation that grew were shrubby grasses.<ref>Levine, p.14</ref> Although city officials were asked to investigate the area, they did not act to solve the problem. Niagara Falls mayor Michael O'Laughlin infamously stated that there was \"nothing wrong\" in Love Canal.\n\nWith further investigation, Gibbs discovered the chemical danger of the adjacent canal. This began her organization's two-year effort to demonstrate that the waste buried by Hooker Chemical was responsible for the health problems of local residents. Throughout the ordeal, homeowners' concerns were ignored not only by Hooker Chemical (now a subsidiary of [[Occidental Petroleum]]), but also by members of government. These parties argued that the area's endemic health problems were unrelated to the toxic chemicals buried in the Canal. Since the residents could not prove the chemicals on their property had come from Hooker's disposal site, they could not prove [[legal liability|liability]]. Throughout the legal battle, residents were unable to sell their properties and relocate.\n\n==== Federal response ====\nOn August 7, 1978, United States President [[Jimmy Carter]] announced a federal health emergency, called for the allocation of federal funds, and ordered the Federal Disaster Assistance Agency to assist the City of Niagara Falls to remedy the Love Canal site.{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=28}} This was the first time in American history that emergency funds were used for a situation other than a natural disaster.<ref name=\"epa.gov\">{{cite news|last=Beck|first=Eckardt C.|title=The Love Canal Tragedy|work=EPA Journal|date=January 1979|url=http://www.epa.gov/aboutepa/history/topics/lovecanal/01.htm|accessdate=February 5, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408141141/http://www.epa.gov/history/topics/lovecanal/01.htm|archive-date=April 8, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>  Carter had trenches built that would transport the wastes to sewers and had home [[sump pump]]s sealed off.{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=28}}\n\n[[United States Congress|Congress]] passed the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability Act (CERCLA), better known as the [[Superfund]] Act. Love Canal became the first entry on the list.<ref name=\"Depalma\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/18/nyregion/love-canal-declared-clean-ending-toxic-horror.html|title=Love Canal Declared Clean, Ending Toxic Horror|last=Depalma|first=Anthony|date=2004-03-18|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=2017-02-16|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217204323/http://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/18/nyregion/love-canal-declared-clean-ending-toxic-horror.html|archive-date=2017-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Superfund|CERCLA]] created a tax on the chemical and petroleum industries and provided broad Federal authority to respond directly to releases or threatened releases of hazardous substances that may endanger public health or the environment. CERCLA also created a [[National Priorities List]], a shortened list of the sites that has priority in cleanup. Love Canal was the first Superfund site on that list. Eventually, the site was cleaned and deleted off the list in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cumulis.epa.gov/supercpad/cursites/csitinfo.cfm?id=0201290|title=EPA Superfund Program: LOVE CANAL, NIAGARA FALLS, NY|last=|first=|date=|website=CERCLA|publisher=[[Environmental Protection Agency]]|access-date=18 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201085600/http://cumulis.epa.gov/supercpad/cursites/csitinfo.cfm?id=0201290|archive-date=1 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Because the Superfund Act contained a \"retroactive liability\" provision, Occidental was held liable for cleanup of the waste even though it had followed all applicable U.S. laws when disposing of it.\n\n==== Health effects ====\nAt first, scientific studies did not conclusively prove the chemicals were responsible for the residents' illnesses yet scientists were divided on the issue, even though eleven known or suspected [[carcinogens]] had been identified, one of the most prevalent being [[benzene]]. Also present was dioxin ([[polychlorinated dibenzodioxins]]) in the water, a very hazardous substance. Dioxin pollution is usually measured in [[parts per trillion]]; at Love Canal, water samples showed dioxin levels of 53 [[parts per billion]] (53,000 parts per trillion).{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=28}} [[Geologist]]s were recruited to determine whether underground [[Swale (geographical feature)|swales]] were responsible for carrying the chemicals to the surrounding residential areas. Once there, chemicals could [[soil contamination|leach]] into [[basement]]s and evaporate into [[Indoor air quality|household air]].\n\nIn 1979, the EPA announced the result of [[blood test]]s which showed high [[white blood cell]] counts, a precursor to [[leukemia]],<ref name=\"epa1\" /> and [[chromosome]] damage in Love Canal residents. 33% of the residents had undergone chromosomal damage. In a typical population, chromosomal damage affects 1% of people.{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=28}} Other studies were unable to find harm.<ref>''Cancer incidence in the Love Canal area.'' Science, v. 212, June 19, 1981: 1404\u20131407. {{pmid|7233229}} \"Data from the New York Cancer Registry show no evidence for higher cancer rates associated with residence near the Love Canal toxic waste burial site in comparison with the entire state outside of New York City.\"</ref><ref>Ember, Lois R. ''Uncertain science pushes Love Canal solutions to political, legal arenas.'' Chemical & Engineering News, v. 58, August 11, 1980: 22\u201329. Relates the chronology of Hooker Chemical Company and the discovery of toxic chemicals at Love Canal and describes the medical research on the former residents to determine the health effects. {{doi|10.1021/cen-v058n032.p022}}</ref><ref>Maugh, Thomas H., 11. ''Health effects of exposure to toxic wastes.'' Science, v. 215, January 29, 1982: 490\u2013493; February 5: 643\u2013647. This two-part series first addresses the question \"Just how hazardous are dumps?\" and then, in \"Biological markers for chemical exposure\", suggests alterations in chromosomes indicate exposure but long term studies will be necessary to determine the severity of effects of health.</ref><ref>''The Risks of living near Love Canal.'' Science, v . 212, August 27, 1982: 808\u2013809, 811. {{doi|10.1126/science.7100924}} {{pmid|7100924}} \"Controversy and confusion follow a report that the Love Canal area is no more hazardous than areas elsewhere in Niagara Falls.\"</ref><ref>[https://digital.library.unt.edu/govdocs/crs//data/1983/upl-meta-pcc-1156152365knordstr_nt104619_unt/83-160L_1983Aug12.pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081031163405/http://digital.library.unt.edu/govdocs/crs//data/1983/upl-meta-pcc-1156152365knordstr_nt104619_unt/83-160L_1983Aug12.pdf |date=2008-10-31 }}\nCongressional Research Service, Report No. 83-160 L, LIABILITY FOR INJURY RESULTING FROM THE DISPOSAL OF HAZARDOUS WASTE: Preliminary Bibliography on the 1983-1984, Intercollegiate Debate Resolution, August 12, 1983</ref> The [[United States National Research Council]] (NRC) surveyed Love Canal health studies during 1991. The NRC noted the major exposure of concern was the groundwater rather than drinking water; the groundwater \"seeped into basements\" and then resulted in exposure through air and soil<ref name=\"NRC1991\" />{{rp|196}} noted several studies reported higher levels of low-birth weight babies and birth defects among the exposed residents<ref name=\"NRC1991\">National Research Council, Committee on Environmental Epidemiology, [http://www.nap.edu/catalog.php?record_id=1802 Environmental Epidemiology, vol. 1: Public Health and Hazardous Wastes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218015704/http://www.nap.edu/catalog.php?record_id=1802 |date=2012-02-18 }} (Washington: National Academy Press, 1991)</ref>{{rp|190\u201391}} with some evidence the effect subsided after the exposure was eliminated.<ref name=\"NRC1991\" />{{rp|165}} The National Research Council also noted a study which found exposed children were found to have an \"excess of seizures, learning problems, hyperactivity, eye irritation, skin rashes, abdominal pain, and incontinence\" and stunted growth.<ref name=\"NRC1991\" />{{rp|196}} [[Vole]]s in the area were found to have significantly increased mortality compared to controls (mean life expectancy in exposed animals \"23.6 and 29.2 days, respectively, compared to 48.8 days\" for control animals).<ref name=\"NRC1991\" />{{rp|215}} New York State also has an ongoing health study of Love Canal residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.health.state.ny.us/environmental/investigations/love_canal/|title=Love Canal|author=|date=|website=www.health.state.ny.us|access-date=2007-08-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814095537/http://www.health.state.ny.us/environmental/investigations/love_canal/|archive-date=2007-08-14|url-status=live}}</ref> In that year, the Albert Elia Building Co., Inc., now Sevenson Environmental Services, Inc., was selected as the principal contractor to re-bury safely the toxic waste at the Love Canal Site.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) in 1979, residents exhibited a \"disturbingly high rate of [[miscarriage]]s ... Love Canal can now be added to a growing list of environmental disasters involving toxics, ranging from industrial workers stricken by [[anxiety disorder|nervous disorders]] and [[cancer]]s to the discovery of toxic materials in the milk of nursing mothers.\" In one case, two out of four children in a single Love Canal family had [[Congenital disorder|birth defects]]; one girl was born [[hearing impairment|deaf]] with a [[cleft palate]], an extra row of teeth, and slight [[mental retardation|retardation]], and a boy was born with an eye defect.<ref name=epa1>{{cite web|url=https://archive.epa.gov/epa/aboutepa/love-canal-tragedy.html|title=The Love Canal Tragedy|first=US|last=EPA, OA, OEAEE, OWC|date=|website=archive.epa.gov|access-date=2017-04-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610141257/https://archive.epa.gov/epa/aboutepa/love-canal-tragedy.html|archive-date=2017-06-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Aftermath ===\n[[File:Love Canal (5621742089).jpg|thumb|Love Canal residents discuss revitalizing their contaminated neighborhood with EPA Administrator [[Lee M. Thomas]] in 1985.]]\nWhen Eckhardt C. Beck (EPA Administrator for Region 2, 1977 \u2013 1979) visited Love Canal during the late 1970s, he discerned the presence of toxic substances in the community:\n\n{{quote|I visited the canal area at that time. Corroding waste-disposal drums could be seen breaking up through the grounds of backyards. Trees and gardens were turning black and dying. One entire swimming pool had been popped up from its foundation, afloat now on a small sea of chemicals. Puddles of noxious substances were pointed out to me by the residents. Some of these puddles were in their yards, some were in their basements, others yet were on the school grounds. Everywhere the air had a faint, choking smell. Children returned from play with burns on their hands and faces.<ref name=epa1 />}}\n\nRobert Whalen, then-New York's Health Commissioner, also visited Love Canal and believed that the Canal constituted an emergency, stating: \"Love Canal Chemical Waste Landfill constitutes a public nuisance and an extremely serious threat and danger to the health, safety and welfare of those using it, living near it or exposed to the conditions emanating from it, consisting among other things, of chemical wastes lying exposed on the surface in numerous places pervasive, pernicious and obnoxious chemical vapors and fumes affecting both the ambient air and the homes of certain residents living near such sites.\"{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=27}} Whalen also instructed people to avoid going into their basements as well as to avoid fruits and vegetables grown in their gardens.  People became very worried because many had consumed produce from their gardens for several years.<ref>Levine, p.29</ref> Whalen urged that all pregnant women and children under the age of two be removed from Love Canal as soon as possible.\n\nThe 99th Street School, on the other hand, was located within the former boundary of the Hooker Chemical landfill site. The school was closed and demolished, but both the school board and the chemical company refused to accept liability. The 93rd Street School was closed some two years later because of concerns about seeping toxic waste.\n\n==== Evacuation ====\nThe lack of public interest in Love Canal made matters worse for the homeowners' association, which was opposed by two organizations that sought to disprove negligence. Initially, members of the association had been frustrated by the lack of a public entity that could advise and defend them. Gibbs met with public resistance from a number of residents within the community. Eventually, the federal government relocated more than 800 families and reimbursed them for the loss of their homes. The state government and federal government used $15 million to purchase 400 homes closest to Love Canal and demolished several rings of houses. {{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n==== Litigation and compensation ====\nIn 1994, Federal District Judge [[John Thomas Curtin|John Curtin]] ruled that Hooker/Occidental had been [[Negligence|negligent]], but not reckless, in its handling of the waste and sale of the land to the [[Niagara Falls School Board]].<ref>U.S. v. Hooker Chemicals and Plastics Corp., 850 Federal Supplement, 993 (W.D.N.Y., 1994)</ref> Curtin's decision also contains a detailed history of events leading up to the Love Canal disaster. [[Occidental Petroleum]] was sued by the EPA and in 1995 agreed to pay $129 million in restitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usdoj.gov/opa/pr/Pre_96/December95/638.txt.html|title=Occidental to pay $129 Million in Love Canal Settlement|date=December 21, 1995|publisher=U.S. Department of Justice|accessdate=2007-02-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060930023208/http://www.usdoj.gov/opa/pr/Pre_96/December95/638.txt.html|archive-date=September 30, 2006|url-status=live}}</ref> Out of that federal lawsuit came money for a small health fund and $3.5 million for the state health study.<ref name=\"justice.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/archive/opa/pr/Pre_96/December95/638.txt.html|title=#638 Occidental to pay $129 million in Love Canal settlement|website=www.justice.gov|access-date=2017-02-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217142819/https://www.justice.gov/archive/opa/pr/Pre_96/December95/638.txt.html|archive-date=2017-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Residents' lawsuits were also settled in the years following the Love Canal disaster.{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=29}}\n\nThe Department of Justice published a report noting that the sites have been successfully remediated and are ready again for use. The Love Canal Area Revitalization Authority sold a few abandoned homes to private citizens. Virtually all remedial activities of the site, other than the operation of the [[leachate]] collection system, were completed by 1989.<ref name=\"justice.gov\" /> [[File:Abandoned Streets in Love Canal.jpg|thumb|Abandoned streets on the west side of Love Canal.]]\n\n==== Remediation ====\n[[File:Looking down 99th Street in Love Canal.jpg|thumb|Looking down 99th Street in Love Canal.]]\nHouses in the residential areas on the east and west sides of the canal were demolished. All that remains on the west side are abandoned residential streets. Some older east side residents, whose houses stand alone in the demolished neighborhood, chose to stay. It was estimated that fewer than 90 of the original 900 families opted to remain.{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=28}} They were willing to remain as long as they were guaranteed that their homes were in a relatively safe area.<ref name=\"Levine, p.215\">Levine, p. 215</ref> On June 4, 1980, the [[Government of New York|state government]] founded the Love Canal Area Revitalization Agency (LCARA) to restore the area. The area north of Love Canal became known as Black Creek Village.  LCARA wanted to resell 300 homes that had been bought by New York when the residents were relocated.<ref name=\"Levine, p.215\"/>  The homes are farther away from where the chemicals were dumped. The most toxic area ({{convert|16|acre|m2}}) was reburied with a thick plastic liner, clay and dirt.  A {{convert|2.4|m||adj=on}} high barbed wire fence was installed around the area.<ref name=\"Jordan, Michael 2003, p.108\">Jordan, Michael, ''Hush Hush: The Dark Secrets of Scientific Research''. Buffalo: Firefly Books, 2003, p.108.</ref> It has been calculated that 248 separate chemicals, including {{convert|60|kg}} of dioxin, have been unearthed from the canal.<ref name=\"Jordan, Michael 2003, p.108\"/>\n\n==== Analysis ====\nIn 1998, Dr. [[Elizabeth Whelan]], founder of industry advocacy group [[American Council on Science and Health]], wrote an editorial about the Canal in which she stated that the media started calling the Canal a \"public health time bomb\", an editorial that created minor hysteria. She declared that people were not falling ill because of exposure to chemical waste, but from stress caused by the media.<ref name=\"Jordan, Michael 2003, p.108\"/>  Besides double the rate of birth defects to children born while living on Love Canal, a follow-up study two decades after the incident \"showed increased risks of low birth weight, congenital malformations and other adverse reproductive events\".<ref name=\"Love Canal Follow-up Health Study\">{{cite web |url=http://www.health.ny.gov/environmental/investigations/love_canal/docs/report_public_comment_final.pdf |title=Love Canal Follow-Up Health Study - Final Report |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2019-07-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815144855/https://www.health.ny.gov/environmental/investigations/love_canal/docs/report_public_comment_final.pdf |archive-date=2019-08-15 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nLove Canal, along with [[Times Beach, Missouri]] and the [[Valley of the Drums|Valley of the Drums, Kentucky]], are important in [[Environmental movement in the United States|United States environmental history]] as three sites that significantly contributed to the passing of the [[Superfund|CERCLA]]. Love Canal \"become the symbol for what happens when hazardous industrial products are not confined to the workplace but 'hit people where they live' in inestimable amounts\".<ref>Levine, p.218</ref>\n\nLove Canal was not an isolated case. Eckardt C. Beck suggested that there are probably hundreds of similar dumpsites.<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/> President Carter declared that discovering these dumpsites was \"one of the grimmest discoveries of the modern era\".<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/> Had the residents of Love Canal been aware that they were residing on toxic chemicals, most would not have moved there in the first place. Beck noted that one main problem remains that ownership of such chemical companies can change over the years, making liability difficult to assign (a problem that would be addressed by CERCLA, or the Superfund Act).<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/>  Beck contended that increased commitment was necessary to develop controls that would \"defuse future Love Canals\".<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/>\n\nThe [[free market environmentalist]] activists have often cited the Love Canal incident as a consequence of government decision-makers not taking responsibility for their decisions. Stroup writes, \"The school district owning the land had a laudable but narrow goal: it wanted to provide education cheaply for district children. Government decision makers are seldom held accountable for broader social goals in the way that private owners are by liability rules and potential profits.\"<ref name=Stroup>{{citation|url=http://www.nesgeorgia.org/files/free_market_environmentalism.pdf|author=Stroup, Richard|title=Free-Market Environmentalism|publisher=The Library of Economics and Liberty|access-date=2010-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405015942/http://www.nesgeorgia.org/files/free_market_environmentalism.pdf|archive-date=2016-04-05|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Conclusion===\nIn 2004, federal officials announced that the Superfund cleanup has ended, albeit cleanup had concluded years prior.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TPwhvm4DfdwC&pg=PT182&lpg=PT182&dq=2004+love+canal#v=onepage&q=2004%20love%20canal&f=false|title=Love Canal|last=JD|first=Penelope Ploughman PhD|date=2013-03-25|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=9781439641996|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=2GURDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT297&lpg=PT297&dq=2004+love+canal#v=onepage&q=2004%20love%20canal&f=false|title=Love Canal: A Toxic History from Colonial Times to the Present|last=Newman|first=Richard S.|date=2016-04-12|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190262846|language=en}}</ref> The entire process occurred over 21 years and costed a total of $400 million.<ref name=\"Depalma\"/> About 260 homes north of the canal have been renovated and sold to new owners, and about {{convert|150|acre|}} east of the canal have been sold to commercial developers for light industrial uses. In total, 950 families had been evacuated. The site was removed from the Superfund list on September 30, 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.epa.gov/epapages/newsroom_archive/newsreleases/40a7e32b0bbe56018525712a006fca02.html|title=09/30/2004: EPA Removes Love Canal from Superfund List|website=archive.epa.gov|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170506021249/https://archive.epa.gov/epapages/newsroom_archive/newsreleases/40a7e32b0bbe56018525712a006fca02.html|archive-date=2017-05-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Controversies related to moved Love Canal waste and reports of illness ===\nThe Niagara Sanitation landfill covers {{convert|18.7|acre|}} in [[Wheatfield, New York]].  The state Department of Transportation moved approximately {{convert|1,600|cuyd|}} of material from the Love Canal landfill to Niagara Sanitation. Residents of [[North Tonawanda]] and Wheatfield suffering severe health problems say the waste was subsequently disturbed during the construction of the LaSalle Expressway in Niagara Falls. The New York Department of Environmental Conservation (DEC) contends there is no proof the landfill leaks. A lawsuit asserts that Hooker's creation of a brine pipeline along the edge of the landfill used to move brine from Wyoming County to its Niagara Falls plant location, may have created a conduit for the landfilled waste to leak out.<ref>[http://buffalonews.com/2017/04/03/draft-landfill-lawsuit/ Residents feel 'trapped' by Wheatfield landfill, once home to Love Canal waste] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822120106/http://buffalonews.com/2017/04/03/draft-landfill-lawsuit/ |date=2017-08-22 }} by Thomas J. Prohaska, ''Buffalo Evening News'', Published Mon, Apr 3, 2017</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nThe legacy of the disaster inspired a fictionalized 1982 made-for-TV film entitled ''Lois Gibbs and the Love Canal''. An award-winning documentary by [[Lynn Corcoran]] entitled ''[[In Our Own Backyard]]'' was released in the U.S. in 1983.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bullfrogfilms.com/catalog/lc.html |title=In Our Own Backyard &#124; Bullfrog Films: 1-800-543-3764: Environmental DVDs and Educational DVDs |publisher=Bullfrog Films |date= |accessdate=2019-07-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716212647/http://www.bullfrogfilms.com/catalog/lc.html |archive-date=2019-07-16 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Modern Marvels]]'' retold the disaster in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.epa.gov/region1/education/pdfs/GREENModule1VideoLinks.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-09-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120709232337/http://www.epa.gov/region1/education/pdfs/GREENModule1VideoLinks.pdf |archive-date=2012-07-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Joyce Carol Oates]] included the story of Love Canal in her 2004 novel ''[[The Falls (Oates novel)|The Falls]]'', but changed the time period of the disaster to the 1960s. The latest history of Love Canal, ''Love Canal: A Toxic History From Colonial Times To The Present'', written by Richard S. Newman, was published by Oxford University Press in 2016.\n\nThe movie ''[[Tootsie]]'' has a character (played by [[Bill Murray]]) attempting to produce a play called \"Return to Love Canal\". In response to the pitch for the play, [[Sydney Pollack]] tells [[Dustin Hoffman]] that \"Nobody wants to produce a play about a couple that moved back to Love Canal. Nobody wants to pay twenty dollars to see people living next to chemical waste. They can see that in [[New Jersey]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0084805/|title=Tootsie|author=Sidney Pollack|date=1982|access-date=2018-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728090352/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0084805/|archive-date=2018-07-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n\"Love Canal\" was also a segment in the premiere episode of [[Michael Moore]]'s television series ''[[TV Nation]]'', which featured realtors attempting to lure prospective residents to the area.\n\nIn the 1998 [[first-person shooter]] [[video game]], ''[[Blood II: The Chosen]]'', the sixth level of the second episode, which takes place in part of the water system of a housing project built by the villains over a pit of radioactive waste, is named \"Love Canal\" in reference to the disaster.\n\n\"Love Canal\" is the name of a 7\" single released by the [[noise-punk]] band [[Flipper (band)|Flipper]] in February 1981. The lyrics are about the disaster.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/grunge-is-dirt-43364/ |title=Grunge is dirt. |author=Mark Arm |date=8 September 2006 |website=www.uncut.co.uk |publisher=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |accessdate=31 January 2020 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917082912/http://www.uncut.co.uk/features/grunge-is-dirt-43364 |archivedate=17 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[102nd Street chemical landfill]], a landfill located immediately to the south of Love Canal.\n* [[Cancer Alley]] (in Louisiana)\n* [[Landfills in the United States]]\n* [[Spring Valley, Washington, D.C.]]\n* [[Times Beach, Missouri]]\n* [[Valley of the Drums]]\n* [[Centralia, Pennsylvania]] and its [[Centralia mine fire|mine fire]]\n* [[William Ginsberg]], member of New York State task force investigating Love Canal in 1979, and author of state report.\n* ''[[The Killing Ground (film)|The Killing Ground]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book|last=Blum|first=Elizabeth D.|title=Love Canal Revisited : Race, Class, and Gender in Environmental Activism\n|publisher=University Press of Kansas|year=2008|location=Kansas|isbn=978-0-7006-1560-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Colten|first1=Craig E.|last2=Skinner|first2=Peter N.|title=The Road to Love Canal: Managing Industrial Waste Before EPA|location=Austin|publisher=University of Texas Press|year=1996|ref=harv|isbn=0292711824|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/roadtolovecanalm0000colt}}\n*{{cite book|last=Levine|first=Adeline Gordon|title=Love Canal: Science, Politics and People|location=Lexington, MA|publisher=D.C. Heath and Company|year=1982|isbn=978-0-669-05411-8|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/lovecanalscience0000levi}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Love Canal}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100613105310/http://library.buffalo.edu/lovecanal/ Love Canal Collections in the University Archives], University at Buffalo Libraries\n* [http://purl.org/net/findingaids/view?docId=ead/bechs/bechs_c94_2.xml Adeline Levine Love Canal Papers] at The [[Buffalo History Museum]]\n* [http://www.lcmf.org/ Love Canal Medical Fund, Inc.]\n* [http://www.nyheritage.org/collections/love-canal-images New York Heritage: Love Canal Images]\n*[https://www.health.ny.gov/environmental/investigations/love_canal/docs/report_public_comment_final.pdf 2008 Follow Up Study]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Love Canal| ]]\n[[Category:Canals in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Disasters in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Environmental issues in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Environmental controversies]]\n[[Category:Environmental disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:Former landfills in the United States]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Niagara Falls, New York]]\n[[Category:Pollution in the United States]]\n[[Category:Superfund sites in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Waste disposal incidents in the United States]]\n[[Category:Environmental disaster ghost towns]]\n[[Category:1978 in the environment]]\n[[Category:Urban decay in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "37.233.66.12", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Love_Canal"}
{"title_page": "Deepika Padukone filmography", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n[[File:Deepika padukone BRM.jpg|alt=A shot of Deepika Padukone|thumb|Padukone in 2016 promoting [[Bajirao Mastani]]]]\n[[Deepika Padukone]] is an Indian actress who appears in [[Bollywood|Hindi films]]. Her first screen appearance was in [[Himesh Reshammiya]]'s music video \"Naam Hai Tera\" in 2005.<ref name=\"video\">{{Cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Deepika-Padukone-in-awe-of-beauty-pageant-winners/articleshow/10767352.cms?referral=PM |title=Deepika Padukone in awe of beauty pageant winners |last=Iyer |first=Meena |date=17 November 2011 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=3 August 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412161455/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Deepika-Padukone-in-awe-of-beauty-pageant-winners/articleshow/10767352.cms?referral=PM |archive-date=12 April 2018}}</ref> Padukone made her film debut by playing the titular role in the [[Kannada]] film  ''[[Aishwarya (film)|Aishwarya]]'' (2006).<ref name=\"debut\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/sep/15aish.htm |title=Deepika's Aishwarya is a must watch |last=Vijayasarathy |first=R.G. |date=15 September 2006 |publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023055429/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/sep/15aish.htm |archive-date=23 October 2013 |access-date=3 August 2013}}</ref> Her first Hindi film release came the following year with [[Farah Khan]]'s melodrama ''[[Om Shanti Om]]'', in which she played dual roles opposite [[Shah Rukh Khan]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/54373 |title=Movie Review: Om Shanti Om |last=Adarsh |first=Taran |date=7 November 2007 |work=[[Bollywood Hungama]] |access-date=18 December 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6JwBYXxYy?url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/54373 |archive-date=27 September 2013}}</ref> For her performance, she won the [[Filmfare Award for Best Female Debut]] and also received a [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] nomination. Her sole film role in 2008 was as one of [[Ranbir Kapoor]]'s love interests in ''[[Bachna Ae Haseeno]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?238292 |title=Movie Review: Bachna Ae Haseeno |last=Joshi |first=Namrata |date=1 September 2008 |work=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |access-date=19 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927152352/http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?238292 |archive-date=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nPadukone's first film release of 2009, the [[Kung fu film|kung fu]] comedy  ''[[Chandni Chowk to China]]'' opposite [[Akshay Kumar]], proved to be a box office flop.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=348&catName=TGlmZXRpbWUgV29ybGR3aWRlIEluIFVTICQ= |title=Top Lifetime Grossers Worldwide (US $) |website=[[Box Office India]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602093609/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=312&catName=TGlmZXRpbWU%3D |archive-date=2 June 2013 |access-date=11 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2009-01-20/news/27650181_1_domestic-box-office-bollywood-film-kinng |title=Chandni Chowk to China crosses Rs 33 cr at local box office |last=Sharma |first=Amit |date=20 January 2009 |work=[[The Economic Times]] |access-date=6 August 2013 |last2=Verma Ambwani |first2=Meenakshi |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305091941/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2009-01-20/news/27650181_1_domestic-box-office-bollywood-film-kinng |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, her next release, [[Imtiaz Ali (director)|Imtiaz Ali]]'s romance ''[[Love Aaj Kal]]'' grossed {{INRConvert|1.2|b}} worldwide,<ref name=\"top\">{{Cite web |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/arounddetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3997&nCat= |title=Top All Time Worldwide Grossers Updated |date=11 May 2012 |website=Box Office India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105215110/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/arounddetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=4409&nCat= |archive-date=5 November 2013 |access-date=13 October 2013}}</ref> and garnered her a second Best Actress nomination at Filmfare.<ref name=\"ff09\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/725/ |title=Nominations for 55th Idea Filmfare Awards 2009 |date=11 February 2010 |work=Bollywood Hungama |access-date=27 April 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020180943/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/725/ |archive-date=20 October 2014}}</ref> Padukone had five film releases in 2010. The comedy ''[[Housefull (2010 film)|Housefull]]'' was a commercial success,<ref name=\"top\" /> though her other four releases failed at the box office.<ref name=\"bo2010\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=318&catName=MjAxMA== |title=Box Office 2010 |publisher=Box office India |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014062657/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=318&catName=MjAxMA%3D%3D |archive-date=14 October 2013 |access-date=14 May 2012}}</ref> The series of poorly received films continued with both her 2011 releases{{mdash}}the drama ''[[Aarakshan]]'' and the comedy ''[[Desi Boyz]]''.<ref name=\"making\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-06-17/news-interviews/40009313_1_deepika-padukone-cocktail-and-deepika-imtiaz-ali |title=The making of Deepika Padukone |last=Pal |first=Chandrima |date=17 June 2013 |work=The Times of India |access-date=27 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627020227/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-06-17/news-interviews/40009313_1_deepika-padukone-cocktail-and-deepika-imtiaz-ali |archive-date=27 June 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The acclaimed role of an impulsive party-girl in [[Homi Adajania]]'s ''[[Cocktail (2012 film)|Cocktail]]'' (2012) proved to be a breakthrough for Padukone and she received several acting nominations for it.<ref name=\"making\" /><ref name=\"awards\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/celebritymicro/awards/id/1856 |title=Deepika Padukone&nbsp;\u2014 Awards |work=Bollywood Hungama |access-date=5 September 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6JwCqDjGs?url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/celebritymicro/awards/id/1856 |archive-date=27 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/cocktail-deepika-padukone-daina-penty-saif-ali-khan/1/207582.html |title=Was conscious about my look in Cocktail: Deepika |work=[[India Today]] |date=11 July 2012 |accessdate=10 August 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6JwCBnq5n?url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/cocktail-deepika-padukone-daina-penty-saif-ali-khan/1/207582.html |archivedate=27 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}<br />{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/critics-verdict-cocktail-works-but-in-bits/story-cFNQiVGyPXFUTKmsSUSBEN.html |title=Critics verdict: Cocktail works, but in bits |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=13 July 2012 |accessdate=7 October 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304122353/http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/critics-verdict-cocktail-works-but-in-bits/story-cFNQiVGyPXFUTKmsSUSBEN.html |archivedate= 4 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\nPadukone found further success in 2013 when all four of her films were box office hits.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/deepika-padukone-lucky-fourth-time-with-ramleela/1196368/ |title=Deepika Padukone lucky fourth time with 'Ram-Leela' |last=Goyal |first=Divya |date=18 November 2013 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |access-date=4 December 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222152120/http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/deepika-padukone-lucky-fourth-time-with-ramleela/1196368/ |archive-date=22 February 2014}}</ref> Among these were two of the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossing Indian films]]{{mdash}}the romantic comedies ''[[Yeh Jawaani Hai Deewani]]'' and ''[[Chennai Express]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=6355&nCat |title=Dhoom 3 All Time Number One Worldwide Grosser: 500 cr Plus Expected |website=Box Office India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102192306/http://boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=6355&nCat |archive-date=2 January 2014 |access-date=3 January 2014}}</ref> She also won the Filmfare Award for Best Actress for playing a character based on [[Juliet]] in [[Sanjay Leela Bhansali]]'s tragic romance ''[[Goliyon Ki Raasleela Ram-Leela]]'' (2013).<ref name=\"ff13\">{{Cite web |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/filmfare-awards-2014-deepika-padukone-wins-best-actress-award-farhan-akhtar-best-actor/447639-8-66.html |title=Filmfare Awards 2014: Deepika Padukone wins Best Actress award, Farhan Akhtar Best Actor |date=25 January 2014 |publisher=[[CNN-IBN]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140125110704/http://ibnlive.in.com/news/filmfare-awards-2014-deepika-padukone-wins-best-actress-award-farhan-akhtar-best-actor/447639-8-66.html |archive-date=25 January 2014 |access-date=25 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-party-girl-deepika-padukone-gets-serious-1819664 |title=Party girl Deepika Padukone gets serious |last=KBR |first=Upala |date=7 April 2013 |work=[[Daily News and Analysis]] |access-date=24 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014003716/http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-party-girl-deepika-padukone-gets-serious-1819664 |archive-date=14 October 2014}}</ref> In 2014, Padukone appeared in the [[Tamil language|Tamil]] animation film ''[[Kochadaiiyaan]]'' and played a bar dancer in the top-grossing heist film ''[[Happy New Year (2014 film)|Happy New Year]]''.<ref name=\"kocha\">{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/deepika-padukone-working-in-kochadaiiyaan-was-an-experience-637867 |title=Deepika Padukone: Working in Kochadaiiyaan was an experience |date=10 March 2014 |publisher=[[NDTV]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627013948/http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/deepika-padukone-working-in-kochadaiiyaan-was-an-experience-637867 |archive-date=27 June 2015 |access-date=23 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/happy-new-year-review-if-indulgences-were-trimmed-this-might-have-been-a-more-enjoyable-film/508330-8-66.html |title='Happy New Year' review |last=Masand |first=Rajeev |date=25 October 2014 |publisher=CNN-IBN |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111041401/http://ibnlive.in.com/news/happy-new-year-review-if-indulgences-were-trimmed-this-might-have-been-a-more-enjoyable-film/508330-8-66.html |archive-date=11 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/Collections/world_total#.VbC_lvmSiYA |title=Top Worldwide Grossers All Time |website=Box Office India |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150919181138/http://boxofficeindia.com/Collections/world_total |archive-date=19 September 2015 |access-date=23 July 2015}}</ref> The following year, she played a headstrong architect in [[Shoojit Sircar]]'s acclaimed comedy-drama ''[[Piku]]'', which earned Padukone her second Best Actress award at Filmfare, and portrayed the warrior [[Mastani]] in Bhansali's highly successful historical romance ''[[Bajirao Mastani]]''.<ref name=\"Chatterjee\">{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie-reviews/piku-movie-review-1124 |title=Piku Movie Review |last=Chatterjee |first=Saibal |date=8 May 2015 |publisher=NDTV |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510190128/http://movies.ndtv.com/movie-reviews/piku-movie-review-1124 |archive-date=10 May 2015 |access-date=10 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/piku-review-roundup-simple-classy-charming-film-631700 |title='Piku' Review Roundup: A Film that's all Heart |last=Mehta |first=Ankita |date=7 May 2015 |work=[[International Business Times]] |access-date=25 January 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150509200624/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/piku-review-roundup-simple-classy-charming-film-631700 |archive-date=9 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Filmfare2016\">{{cite news|title=Full list of winners of the 61st Britannia Filmfare Awards |url=http://www.filmfare.com/news/full-list-of-winners-of-the-61st-britannia-filmfare-awards-11841.html |work=[[Filmfare]] |date=15 January 2016 |accessdate=16 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316165017/http://www.filmfare.com/news/full-list-of-winners-of-the-61st-britannia-filmfare-awards-11841.html |archivedate=16 March 2016 }}<br />{{cite web|last=Sharma |first=Dhriti |title='Bajirao Mastani' Box Office collection: Ranveer-Deepika-Priyanka's love triangle sees massive growth, mints Rs 181.01 cr |url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/bajirao-mastani-box-office-collection-ranveer-deepika-priyankas-love-triangle-sees-massive-growth-mints-rs-181-01-cr_1846158.html |publisher=[[Zee News]] |date=17 January 2016 |accessdate=25 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120105904/http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/movies/bajirao-mastani-box-office-collection-ranveer-deepika-priyankas-love-triangle-sees-massive-growth-mints-rs-181-01-cr_1846158.html |archivedate=20 January 2016 }}</ref><ref name